<DOCNO> AP880404-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the night betsy wilson first appeared in public 
after losing part of her jaw to cancer in 1972 she was leaving a 
tennis stadium when she caught a young boy staring at her twisted 
and misshapen mouth 
i just went baaah like i was some sort of a monster it made 
me embarrassed and it made me laugh said mrs wilson and it 
made me deal with it 
the left side of her lower jaw had been removed because of an 
unusual lip cancer that traveled along the nerves of her face 
radiation killed the cancer and a bone bank provided her with a new 
jaw but it left her permanently disfigured 
the 55yearold concord resident still gets stares but she no 
longer thinks of herself as monstrouslooking instead she is 
using what she learned from the deformity to organize and promote a 
national mutualhelp network she started last year called lets 
face it 
mrs wilson the mother of two sons and a daughter says others 
with facial deformities need to overcome their isolation and 
negotiate a world that sees them as different and sometimes 
frightening 
everyone reacts differently thats the hard thing youre 
constantly surprised youre not looking at yourself and you 
forget but youre constantly reminded she said this weekend in 
an interview from berkeley calif where she was visiting her 
daughter and husband and making contacts 
mutual help is the thing its not complicated its 
costeffective she said 
lets face it which is based in concord has 200 official 
members in 30 cities and a mailing list of 2000 but it is 
estimated there are 450000 new cases of facial disfigurement each 
year in this country from auto accidents burns cancer and birth 
defects she said 
mrs wilson wants to help them help each other but it takes 
time largely because of the reluctance of such individuals to 
accept themselves 
it took me years and i mean years to do my grieving over 
losing my face she said but denial is also such protection 
it helps you survive 
lets face it provides such resources as lists of organizations 
that help the facially disfigured educational films and videotapes 
and books 
family members need help too the patient is the pebble 
dropped in the pond of the family she said 
in the wake of her illness mrs wilson and her husband jack 
separated he moved to california where he is dean of a law 
school they stay in touch but she said that if lets face it 
existed in the 1970s they might still be together 
we were traumatized we didnt know how to talk about our 
feelings and were still learning our sexuality was invaded 
and we didnt know how to deal with it except to be afraid 
the first lets face it was founded three years ago by a british 
woman christine piff her experiences losing her palate and left 
eye to cancer were recounted in her book lets face it 
mrs wilson read the book then went to england to meet ms piff 
before starting the american branch of lets face it which also 
has members in australia canada new zealand and south africa 
we have a body and we have a spirit and i wasnt given much of 
a choice mrs wilson said i cant hide behind being an 
attractive woman 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

