<TEXT>
since a pair of rabbits arrived 30 
easters ago owners of the happy chick farm north of gulfport have 
been forced into the fishbait business by necessity 
evolved from a 4h club project outgrown by the children of 
marie and howard mays the farm has produced thousands of bunnies 
and billions of worms and crickets 
but im not directly into easter business howard mays said 
friday everything i have is breeder stock but weve had pet 
shops calling all afternoon 
the rabbits live in cages suspended above worm beds gravity 
fertilizes the earthworm habitat with bunny byproducts an 
innovation sprung from necessity 
the odor got bad so we got into the worm business mrs 
mays said 
with the help of eight employees the mays market 2 million 
wigglers per week after a worm harvest the leftover bedding dirt 
is sold to gardeners profits from the highlyprized potting soil 
keep mrs mays driving a new car 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a onetime rivalry between residents 
over whose chickens produced the hardest eggs has turned into a 
homecoming for this eastern tennessee community 
natives from as far away as california and iowa visited sunday 
to tap colored easter eggs together in a 165yearold contest to 
see whose withstands the blows best 
the event dubbed the peters hollow egg fight began in 1823 
when the folks of rome hollow claimed the shells of their eggs were 
harder than those laid in peters hollow down the creek 
the eggs are tapped small end to small end while the contestants 
stand in a circle until only the hardest one is left 
some families keep carefully guarded secrets about the way their 
eggs are boiled and colored and what they feed their chickens 
gebe ritchie who has been chief judge and master of ceremonies 
for 27 years said every shellhardening trick in the book has been 
tried 
one year i disqualified someone who put his eggs in the 
freezer for a year he said 
about 300 people showed up for this years contest the top four 
finishers in the junior and adult competitions received trophies 
</TEXT>
