<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to block the 
federal trade commission from investigating allegedly 
anticompetitive practices of state agencies that license and 
regulate professionals 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that ftc 
investigators may subpoena members of a massachusetts board that 
regulates pharmacies in the state 
officials from 19 states joined massachusetts in urging the 
court to limit the ftcs power the state officials said the 
commission is interfering improperly with their authority 
the commission in 1985 launched its investigation of the 
massachusetts pharmacy registration board 
the board consists of six pharmacists and a public member 
appointed to fiveyear terms by the governor 
federal investigators are questioning whether three of the 
boards rules restrain competition illegally 
one rule bans advertising claims of professional superiority a 
second prohibits mailorder business by druggists and a third 
forbids socalled pickup stations that permit customers to 
pick up prescriptions at branch outlets 
the commission sought to subpoena pharmacy board members to 
determine whether the rules unreasonably restrict advertising and 
customer convenience 
a federal judge ruled that the commission has the power to 
question the board members and the decision was upheld by the 1st 
us circuit court of appeals 
the appeals court rejected arguments by massachusetts officials 
that the pharmacy board is carrying out state policy and thus is 
exempt from antitrust attack the appeals court raised the 
possibility that a board composed almost entirely of pharmacists 
might be imposing private restraints rather than carrying out 
public policy 
the reagan administration supported the appeals court ruling 
justice department lawyers said the subpoenas should be enforced to 
determine whether there is a legitimate state claim to antitrust 
immunity 
but officials from massachusetts and 19 other states said it is 
a case of improper federal intrusion potentially affecting 
regulation by hundreds of state boards 
as governments exercising traditional regulatory powers to 
protect the public health and safety the states are uniquely 
qualified to testify to the importance of the question presented 
in this case state officials said in urging reversal of the 
appeals court ruling 
the states supporting massachusetts appeal are alabama 
arizona delaware hawaii idaho illinois kansas louisiana 
michigan mississippi missouri new hampshire new jersey new 
mexico north carolina oklahoma oregon tennessee and west 
virginia 
the case is monahan vs ftc 871015 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

