a substantial federal 
question refused to hear arguments that the law confiscates 
landlords property by limiting yearly rent increases for 
apartments to 75 percent 
the law covering buildings constructed before 1947 was 
challenged by owners of manhattan apartment buildings converted to 
cooperatives in the early 1970s 
tenants in the buildings who chose not to buy their apartments 
were allowed by law to remain as renters and have been subject to 
annual rent increases of 75 percent since then 
the landlords said the increases limit their rate of return on 
the property to approximately 1 or 2 percent even though real 
estate values in new york city have skyrocketed 
a rate of return of about 2 percent is so unreasonably low 
that it amounted to confiscation of the property the landlords 
said 
it is simply unfair and unconstitutional to select a 
particular class of property owners and force them to donate their 
property to a public purpose and make them finance a public benefit 
that should be the responsibility of the entire population the 
landords lawyers said 
their appeal also said the rent controls are in conflict with 
another provision of new york city law aimed at giving landlords an 
85 percent return on their property 
the longterm effect of the rent controls will be to discourage 
new investment in rental housing and cause deterioration of 
apartment buildings the appeal contended 
the new york state division of housing and community renewal 
defended the rent controls 
state officials said the law balances the interest of 
landlords while preventing precipitous rent hikes in order to 
prevent uncertainty hardship and dislocation to tenants 
the challenge to the new york city law was dismissed in 1987 by 
a state appeals court in a threeparagraph ruling 
the nations highest court last feb 24 upheld a rent control 
ordinance in san jose calif that was attacked as violating the 
constitutional rights of landlords the san jose law permits 
officials to consider a tenants financial hardship in deciding 
whether to grant rent increases 
the case is greene vs mirabel 871212 
