<TEXT>
democrats and republicans on a house committee 
are calling for more federal spending on mental health services to 
improve a piecemeal system they say isnt meeting the needs of 
patients or those trying to help them 
drastic cuts in staff and funding have crippled efforts to 
address the problems that states and communities have in serving 
the mentally ill concludes a report adopted by all members of 
the government operations committee 
the report cites a 30 percent drop in grant money for community 
services and an 88 percent staff cut in a federal division that 
provides technical help to states and localities it says both 
spending and staff levels must be restored to pre1981 status or 
higher 
the release of the report sunday marks the first time that a 
very diverse bipartisan congressional panel has issued such a 
critical report on the federal role in providing mental health 
services said rep ted weiss dny chairman of the 
subcommittee that did the investigation 
according to the report the government is spending 73 billion 
a year on mental health services but they are often fragmented 
inappropriate ineffective or simply lacking 
in addition it said 75 percent of services to the mentally ill 
are provided in communities but outpatient and community services 
receive only 30 percent of the federal money spent in the area 
nearly 29 million americans are victims of some form of mental 
illness that requires professional treatment since the 1960s the 
trend has been to treat patients in community rather than 
institutional settings but the report cited a desperate lack of 
community services for the most severely mentally ill 
the federal government through the alcohol drug abuse and 
mental health administration was spending 606 million for 
community mental health services in 1980 the committee report 
said the amount decreased 14 percent to 5194 million the next 
year and another 18 percent to 4281 million in 1982 
by this year the amount had risen to 643 million but still 30 
percent below the 1980 level when inflation is taken into account 
the committee report said 
the national institute of mental health runs a community support 
program designed to encourage the provision of housing job 
training social services and treatment for the mentally ill the 
program has won wide praise but is severely underfunded the 
committee said 
social security disability insurance supplemental security 
income medicaid and medicare provide living and treatment funds to 
the mentally ill but the report said some victims are unable to 
cope with the complex application process in ohio for example 
only 12 percent of those eligible for the first two programs 
receive the benefits it said 
an 88 percent staff cut occurred at the nimh division of 
education and service system liaison which provides technical 
assistance to states and localities 
the report said 290 people were working at the main office and 
regional offices in 1980 but the office of management and budget 
ordered all regional offices closed and only 35 people remain at 
the main office 
administration witnesses at a hearing last year defended the 
staff and funding cuts the committee report said but the acting 
nimh director conceded that certainly additional resources might 
enrich what were doing 
committee republicans acknowledged in an addendum to the report 
that many of the problems it identified stem from a shortage of 
federal dollars 
we do not dispute the fact that additional financial resources 
would enable states and local communities to assist more mentally 
ill individuals the gop members said they said that in light of 
restrictions on federal spending new money should be spent in 
highpriority areas such as treatment of the severely mentally ill 
young adults and the elderly 
