<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken monday by the supreme court 
 
airport demonstrations 
 
the court refused to let a st louis airport ban all 
demonstrations soliciting and distribution of political and 
religious literature from its terminals 
the justices without comment let stand rulings that an airport 
terminal like a city street and sidewalk is a public forum where 
freespeech rights must be accommodated 
the case is st louis vs jamison 87943 
 
libel 
 
the court let stand a 3 million libel award won by a cigarette 
manufacturer against cbs and a television anchorman in chicago 
the court without comment rejected arguments that the award 
one of the largest libel verdicts ever upheld on appeal violated 
the rights of the network and its newscaster 
the case is cbs vs brown amp williamson 871354 
 
kal 
 
the court agreed to review rulings limiting korean air lines 
financial liability for a 1983 disaster in which 269 people died 
the shooting down of a kal passenger jet over soviet airspace 
the justices said they will study arguments that the airline 
should have to face more than 75000 in damages for each death 
the case is in re kal disaster 871055 
 
regulators 
 
the court refused to block the federal trade commission from 
investigating allegedly anticompetitive practices of state 
agencies that license and regulate professionals 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that ftc 
investigators may subpoena members of a massachusetts board that 
regulates pharmacies in the state 
the case is monahan vs ftc 871015 
 
hospitals 
 
the court reinforced the right of hospitals to challenge federal 
regulations limiting the amount of money they are reimbursed for 
treating medicare patients 
justice anthony m kennedy wrote the unanimous opinion his 
first since joining the court feb 18 
the justices in a case from ohio upheld the right of hospitals 
to appeal certain unfavorable regulations to a governmental agency 
called the provider reimbursement review board 
the case is bethesda hospital association vs bowen 861764 
 
federal labor relations 
 
the court gave federal agencies more leeway in dealing with 
labor unions representing their employees 
the justices in a unanimous and unsigned opinion said a 
federal employers rules or regulations may not be challenged as 
unfair labor practices until found to have been imposed without any 
compelling need 
the case is flra vs aberdeen proving ground 861715 
 
equal voting 
 
the court agreed to decide whether new york citys powerful 
board of estimate must be reapportioned to meet equalvoting 
standards 
the court said it will hear an appeal by city officials who said 
applying the oneperson onevote rule to the governing body will 
undermine its ability to balance regional and local interests 
the case is board of estimate vs morris 871022 
 
 
alaska birds 
 
the court rejected an appeal by alaska natives who want to hunt 
migratory birds in the spring and summer 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that treaties 
between the united states and other nations generally ban the 
hunting between march 10 and sept 1 
the case is alaska federation of natives vs alaska fish and 
wildlife federation 871157 
 
rent control 
 
the court rejected a challenge to new york citys rent control 
law 
the justices citing the lack of a substantial federal 
question refused to hear arguments that the law confiscates 
landlords property by limiting yearly rent increases for 
apartments to 75 percent 
the case is greene vs mirabel 871212 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
