<TEXT>
the supreme court agreed monday to examine the 
authority of federal judges to secondguess decisions by pension 
and welfare plans that deny benefits to workers 
the court said it will hear an appeal by firestone tire amp rubber 
co in a case stemming from the sale of its plastics division in 
1980 
firestone sold the division to occidental petroleum corp the 
sale affected some 500 workers at firestone plants in pottstown 
pa west caldwell nj perryville and salisbury md and baton 
rouge la 
nearly all the employees were given the opportunity to keep 
their jobs under the new ownership and most accepted 
the workers also sought certain benefits from firestone 
including early retirement and severance pay that were included in 
the companys pension and welfare plan 
the company denied the benefits it also refused to give the 
workers information they requested about the benefit plan on 
grounds they no longer were employed by firestone 
the workers sued in federal court charging the company violated 
the federal employee retirement and income security act of 1974 
erisa 
a judge threw out the suit on grounds that firestone did not act 
in an arbitrary and capricious manner 
but the 3rd us circuit court of appeals reinstated the suit 
the appeals court said workers claims must be examined more 
closely in cases in which the administrator of a benefit plan is 
the sole source of its funds such as firestone and is not a 
neutral manager 
the appeals court also said the workers are eligible for damages 
from firestone for its refusal to provide information on benefits 
even though they no longer work for firestone 
the us chamber of commerce and the national association of 
manufacturers supported firestones appeal to the supreme court 
the fundamental purpose of employee benefit plan 
administrators is to make benefit determinations and to manage 
assets the business groups said it is unreasonable to assume 
that congress intended courts to secondguess plan administrators 
by subjecting their decisions to such federal court review 
they said there are some 750000 pension plans run by single 
employers and more than 4 million company welfare plans most of 
which are employeradministered 
the case is firestone vs bruch 871054 
</TEXT>
