<TEXT>
fortythree percent of imported aerosol 
cosmetics contained chlorofluorocarbon compounds banned as 
propellants by the united states 10 years ago the customs service 
said monday 
the noncompliance rate is below some spot checks in the past 
according to don cousins chief of the technical branch in the 
office of technical services in the customs service the figure has 
been as high as 60 percent he said 
customs has never before undertaken anything like the current 
checks in operation ozone which spokesman dennis shimkoski 
said constituted pretty near 100 percent of all pending imports 
the service checked 442 samples of aerosol products since feb 
15 said shimkoski of those 188 contained the offending compounds 
more than 60 different products were represented in the samples 
shimkoski said most were perfumes made in france but deodorants 
baby powders and shaving creams also were found 
shimkoski said the hunch of the service was that most of the 
shipments were not sent to the united states by the manufacturers 
but by middlemen who saw a good deal on something 
the aerosol cosmetics were held up during the lab tests and 
those that flunked could be seized by the service or returned to 
the shipper said shimkoski he said he did not have figures on how 
often each course had been followed 
the united states banned almost all use of chlorofluorocarbon 
or cfc compounds as aerosol propellants in 1978 out of concern 
that they might be attacking the ozone layer 15 to 25 miles high 
that shields the earth from the harmful ultraviolet rays of the sun 
the 1978 us aerosol ban joined only by canada and some of the 
scandinavian countries was the first action anywhere against cfcs 
it was followed by temporary declines in cfc use and inactivity on 
almost every front except research 
more recently scientists concluded that cfcs most likely are 
responsible for unexplained ozone declines at northern 
midlatitudes ranging from 17 percent to 30 percent according to 
a march 15 report from the national aeronautics and space 
administration and also the halving of ozone over the south pole 
in the spring 
less ozone means more ultraviolet reaching the ground and more 
skin cancer the environmental protection agency has estimated that 
a 1 percent decline in ozone means an eventual increase of 48 
percent to 75 percent in the most common form of skin cancer 
last septembers treaty by major producing nations to cut cfc 
emissions by 50 percent by 1998 means other countries probably will 
make action against aerosols their first step industry analysts 
have said 
about 35 percent of cfcs used outside the united states are used 
for aerosols epa has estimated some 5 percent of us use is 
devoted to aerosols mostly in medical applications for which their 
is no good substitute 
cfcs valued for being nontoxic and nonflammable are also 
used as cleaning solvents in electronics manufacture plastic foam 
blowing agents and as refrigeration fluids 
they were largely replaced in us aerosols by flammable 
hydrocarbon compounds which can slightly promote the formation of 
ozone at ground level where it is a pollutant 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0115 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
ethiopia and somalia which fought 
a fullscale war 11 years ago agreed to restore diplomatic 
relations and discuss border disputes dating back more than a 
century ethiopias foreign minister said monday 
berhanu bahiy released details of a 10point agreement worked 
out between the east african neighbors during the weekend by an 
ethiopian delegation he led and a somali delegation led by deputy 
prime minister ahmed mohamoud farah 
under the agreement the two sides will refrain from the use 
of threat or use of force against the territorial integrity or 
political independence of the other 
the two sides also would move their forces back at least six to 
nine miles from the border the withdrawal is to begin by april 15 
and to be completed by may 15 under the supervision of a joint 
military committee 
both sides agreed to exchange prisoners of war within four 
months and to prevent all acts of destabilization and subversive 
activities against each other somalia and ethiopia have 
supported and harbored rebels opposed to the others government 
ethiopias central government has fought long wars with 
separatists in its northernmost regions of eritrea and tigray 
rebels in both regions last week claimed major victories prompting 
president mengistu haile mairiam to comment publicly on the 
problems for the first time in his 13year rule 
somali president mohamed siad barres government also is 
fighting insurgencies 
any lessening of tension between ethiopia and somalia would free 
troops from the border for redeployment to areas of rebel activity 
in 197778 ethiopia and somalia went to war after somalia 
invaded the ogaden a semiarid region of eastern ethiopia 
populated by ethnic somalis 
previously ethiopia had insisted that the border question be 
included in the agenda but somalia proposed that the two sides 
first restore relations and take other steps before tackling the 
question separately 
berhanu said the boundary question would be discussed later but 
said no date had been set 
the agreement was signed after talks friday and saturday in 
mogadishu the somali capital it is based on a march 30 1964 
pact known as the khartoum agreement 
the 1964 agreement which took its name from the sudanese 
capital where it was signed was never honored by either side 
the 1977 invasion by somalia then backed by moscow sparked a 
war that ended a year later when ethiopias marxist government 
routed the invaders and pushed them back across the border by 
then ethiopia had millions of dollars in weapons from its new 
backer the soviet union and help from cuban troops 
ethiopia had been one of the wests staunchest african friends 
before emperor haile selassie was overthrown in a 1974 revolution 
but moscows switch put addis ababa firmly in the soviet camp 
somalia then sought and received us backing 
ethiopia has the largest military force in black africa but the 
conflict with somalia has been a stalemate since the 1977 war 
despite a technical state of war and some border clashes 
</TEXT>
