<TEXT>
the popular myth may be of a caveman 
dragging off his women by her hair but women were probably behind 
many of the major inventions of prehistoric times a researcher 
said monday 
women may be responsible for the major technological 
innovations in prehistory the invention of pottery horticulture 
and agriculture basketmaking weaving and textiles said joan 
gero 
ms gero an assistant professor of anthropology at the 
university of south carolina is one of the organizers of an 
international conference to discuss womens roles in prehistory 
the fiveday conference which opens tuesday at the wedge 
plantation near georgetown is the first archaeological 
conference designed to separate out gender roles in prehistory 
she said 
seventeen researchers including archaeologists 
anthropologists historians and a philosopher will gather for the 
meeting 
included in the group are three noted researchers irene 
silverblatt of the smithsonian institution peter white of the 
university of sydney and henrietta moore an anthropologist from 
cambridge university 
much of what will be discussed flies in the face of the 
conventional wisdom for instance its generally a given in 
archaeological circles that man was the toolmaker in prehistoric 
times ms gero said 
but some researchers are suggesting that based on clues from 
the past and observations of presentday preindustrial societies 
that women were responsible for making tools and pottery 
the irony is that huge chunks of the archaeological record may 
in fact be the result of womens labor ms gero said eighty 
percent of the archaeologists in the world use pottery to sort out 
time periods 
separating the female roles from the male roles in prehistoric 
societies is a real challenge its so hard to do thats why its 
gone so long undone ms gero said 
she noted that while unearthing a pharaohs tomb gives 
scientists clues as to how a small group of people lived were 
looking for half the human race 
one thing we hope will come out of this is an inspection of 
what it means to be female and what it means to be male she 
said we have a notion of females women dont make tools but 
women were responsible for making a lot of stone tools 
often she said people consider the past in terms of their 
present day thinking on what is male and female 
you dont want to say women did exactly what theyre doing 
now she said if we can envision the roles that women played 
in the past that itself is a means to get at what male and female 
mean in different societies 
</TEXT>
