<TEXT>
the government will stop supporting more than 
3000 performing arts companies and let them make their own way in 
the marketplace an official newspaper said monday 
the plan worries some in chinas 56 minority groups who fear 
losing their cultural heritage the englishlanguage china daily 
said it appears to be in keeping with recent steps away from the 
20yearold iron ricebowl policy guaranteeing workers food 
shelter and clothing regardless of their output 
gao zhanxiang vice minister of culture said china will move 
slowly in reforming the management and structure of arts companies 
the newspaper reported he said 210000 professional performers 
will be affected 
recent developments show the need for reform gao said and 
proclaimed it the only way to revive and develop the performing 
arts 
li moran a wellknown stage actor contended the plan would 
throw products of the performing arts into the market as 
commodities china daily reported 
critics were quoted as saying it would leave funding available 
for only modern arts leaving the traditional and minority fields 
completely on their own 
members of traditional and minority musical dance and opera 
troupes have been especially furious with the proposed plans 
china daily said 
under the current system central and local governments control 
hiring budgets and choice of programs under the new one 
companies would have financial autonomy but the government still 
would set culture and entertainment policy 
china daily said most arts companies are overstaffed and 
performers are paid according to seniority it said chinese theater 
has not satisfied the popular needs and lamented the loss of 
talented artists to foreign countries arts in china suffered 
heavily during the 196676 cultural revolution against 
intellectuals which leading chinese directors and actors say 
created a shortage of able young performers 
the cultural ministry said it will sponsor a national conference 
next month to establish procedures for the reforms 
</TEXT>
