<TEXT>
india paid sri lankas main tamil 
separatist leader to cooperate with an agreement intended to end 
the rebel war with the sinhalese majority the indian ambassador 
said monday 
jn dixit said velupillai prabhakaran leader of the liberation 
tigers of tamil eelam asked for the money in new delhi last july 
to replace taxes his militia collected from people in jaffna 
the main tiger stronghold in northern sri lanka 
india agreed to it and some money was paid dixit said 
since then the tigers rejected the peace accord signed last 
july 29 by prime minister rajiv gandhi of india and president 
junius r jayewardene of sri lanka indian forces sent to enforce 
it have been fighting the tamil militia since october 
more than 400 indian soldiers and 1000 tamil militiamen have 
been reported killed about 7000 people have been slain since the 
tamil war began in 1983 
the newspaper indian post reported the payments in an article 
sunday in confirming the story dixit said he did not know the 
amount given prabhakaran but it was enough to take care of his 
requests at that point in time 
an unidentified tiger spokesman was quoted in the post as saying 
the agreement with india was for 384600 a month but no payment 
was made after the first month by then the tigers were 
criticizing the peace accord 
gandhi negotiated the agreement after trying for nearly three 
years to mediate peace between the tamils and the government 
tamil militants want a tamil nation called eelam in northern and 
eastern sri lanka 
about 60 million tamils live in india most of them in tamil 
nadu state across the narrow palk strait from sri lanka most 
tamils are hindu and sinhalese are predominantly buddhist 
ethnic tamils make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million 
people and say the sinhalese who control the government and 
military discriminate against them 
dixit said prabhakaran asked gandhi for the money during 
meetings in new delhi before the peace agreement was signed 
the tigers did not sign the accord but agreed to give up almost 
all their arms the agreement calls for the rebels to disarm in 
exchange for greater tamil autonomy 
