<TEXT>
a judge began a painstaking series of 
interviews monday with about 100 prospective jurors for the retrial 
of a defendant originally sentenced to death in the notorious alday 
family slayings 
superior court judge hugh lawson said he expected the jury 
questioning for the retrial of wayne carl coleman to last at least 
through friday 
coleman is one of three men who were convicted of six counts of 
murder in the case in 1974 and sentenced to die those convictions 
were overturned in 1985 by a federal appeals court which said 
publicity about the case in tiny seminole county made it impossible 
for the three to get fair trials there 
defense lawyer robert h citronberg referred to colemans 
original trial in arguing that potential jurors should not see 
seminole county sheriff jerry godby in the courtroom while they are 
being interviewed for the retrial in dekalb county 
lawson refused to bar godby saying prospective jurors were 
unlikely to notice him since he was not in uniform 
the judge then began calling prospective jurors one at a time 
asking them if they had any moral objections to the death penalty 
and if they could make the lifeordeath choices in a capital 
murder case 
citronberg and fellow defense lawyer tom west asked if the 
prospective jurors would be sympathetic to a defendants mental 
condition deprived upbringing and alcohol or drug abuse 
lawson called the questioning a preliminary screening procedure 
with final selection of jurors possible next week the jury will be 
sequestered for one to two weeks of testimony in the trial the 
judge said 
coleman his halfbrother carl isaacs and george dungee were 
escapees from a maryland prison when they were arrested for the 
slayings of six members of the ned alday family in extreme 
southwestern georgia 
alday his brother and three sons were shot one by one on may 
14 1973 when they arrived at the home of one of the sons where 
coleman and his companions were interrupted in a burglary 
according to testimony 
the wife of one of aldays sons was taken to a wood six miles 
away where she was raped and killed 
isaacs was again convicted of murder and sentenced to death in a 
retrial in perry in january dungee is to be retried in columbus 
after colemans retrial 
</TEXT>
