panama at his request to meet with noriega jackson described 
mcsween as a friend of 20 years who was originally from panama 
using rhetoric from his recent speeches jackson said us 
policy has been misguided 
weve set the forest on fire to smoke one person out he 
said referring to us economic sanctions that have contributed to 
a financial collapse in panama jackson said he did not plan a trip 
to panama 
fitzwater also criticized jacksons involvement in the noriega 
matter we have a bipartisan coordinated plan for dealing with 
noriega thats why its important to congress and the public and 
we believe its been working he said 
jesses been involved in a number of these kinds of mediation 
efforts hes offered to go to libya and cuba and all kinds of 
places fitzwater said 
asked about published accounts over the weekend in which deposed 
panamanian president eric arturo delvalle rejected any notion of 
us military force to get noriega out fitzwater replied he 
says that because he thinks the economic sanctions are working 
that we just need to give these things a chance to kind of 
percolate through the system rather than try to take any more 
action 
fitzwater reiterated that the united states plans no further 
immediate steps beyond the economic sanctions and the deployment 
tuesday of an additional 1300 us military forces to the troubled 
country 
he said the troops were to reinforce our security efforts in 
panama to make sure we have the capability of protecting american 
citizens there if that should become necessary but theres no 
steps beyond that at this point 
mrs oakley meanwhile escalated the administrations criticism 
of panamanian authorities over an incident sunday in which us 
ambassador arthur davis was pursued for two miles in panama city by 
a government military vehicle with its siren blaring 
we consider any threat to the safety of the ambassador to be 
serious as always she said we will take the necessary steps 
to protect americans i am condemning the incident from the podium 
we regard the action as deliberate harassment 
embassy spokesman terence kneebone said davis was leaving the 
home of vatican ambassador jose sebastian laboa when the panamanian 
vehicle began following immediately picking them up right 
outside the gate he said it tried to stop the chauffeurdriven 
car with its lights and sirens 
the ambassadors driver in accordance with instructions did 
not stop the ambassador was driven to his residence and the other 
vehicle followed all the way kneebone said the residences are 
about two miles apart 
