<TEXT>
a 25pound lobster with claws the size of 
baseball mitts that was saved from becoming an easter dinner 
arrived in maine on monday on the final leg of a roundabout journey 
back to the sea 
maine marine officials gently placed shirley a male 
estimated at 40 to 125 years and a 19pound companion lobster 
into a 600gallon tub of icy saltwater after their flight from 
philadelphia freed from their icepacked travel boxes the 
lobsters immediately began moving their giant claws around 
very good hes moving around already thats a good sign 
col robert fogg chief of the bureau of marine patrol of the maine 
department of marine resources said of shirley a real weak 
lobster would be very lifeless 
theyre excellent im pleased with the way theyve shown up 
marine officials planned to return the crustacean behemoths to 
the atlantic early tuesday off cape elizabeth if they remained 
healthly overnight 
this is symbolic of what were trying to do and what citizens 
are trying to do for a natural sustainable resource fogg said 
by protecting these large lobsters theres more of a chance of 
them reproducing and perpetuating the industry 
maine law protects lobsters with body shells longer than five 
inches covering lobsters larger than 4 to 5 pounds 
if the lobsters health deteriorated during the night and they 
could not be saved lt joseph fessenden of the maine bureau of 
marine patrol said the largest would be turned over to the maine 
state museum 
theyre looking for a lobster to stuff he said 
shirley and the companion lobster had been trucked to 
philadelphia from long island ny and sold for 287 after 
crustacean rights advocates took up the cause kevin hill owner of 
hills main line seafood co in the suburb of ardmore persuaded 
the buyer to take 45 pounds of smaller lobsters instead 
hill put the lobsters in a window tank for the rest of their 
visit to philadelphias main line he acknowledged that saving 
lobsters from dinner palates was something new for him which is 
all right 
he also said that the lobsters had been good business as 
thousands of peole dropped by for a look at shirley 
its been very good for business if they dont buy now at 
least they know where we are said hill who planned to travel to 
maine to be on hand for the lobsters release into the atlantic 
hill delayed packing the lobsters for their trip until the last 
possible minute believe it or not im still getting people 
coming by the window to look at em he said monday 
pity not cruelty inc a small animal rights group made 
arrangements with maine officials to turn the creatures loose and 
assumed the 40 flight cost 
if it seems to be a lot of fuss over a couple of lobsters group 
vice president gloria felschercohen makes no apologies 
why not these two lobsters have survived hazards 
particularly shirley over 100 years she said why should she 
need to succumb to the cruelest predator of all man 
