a judge bowed to objections from news 
organizations and lifted an order barring reporting on jury 
selection monday at the cocainesale trial of john zaccaro jr son 
of former vice presidential candidate geraldine ferraro 
the 24yearold zaccaro is charged with selling a quarter gram 
of the drug to an undercover officer two years ago while a senior 
at middlebury college the offense carries a penalty of up to five 
years in prison and a 10000 fine 
zaccaro on monday entered the courtroom separately from his 
parents ferraro and john zaccaro sr as the longdelayed trial 
began but they sat immediately behind their son 
in questioning of at least seven potential jurors monday none 
said ferraros candidacy would have any affect on how they would 
judge her son 
several panelists expressed strong sentiments about drugs one 
juror who was dismissed said id probably be the one going to 
jail if i catch someone selling drugs to my kid 
judge francis mccaffrey after a meeting with attorneys had 
imposed an gag order and said only six reporters could attend jury 
selection he said that he expects the process to last three days 
and that any information published could prejudice the jury pool 
it is important that we get an impartial jury that is where 
you persons have become an issue mccaffrey told the 11 reporters 
in the courtroom clearly segregated voir dire is appropriate in 
this case 
however after an afternoon hearing on a challenge from several 
news organizations mccaffery lifted the order but he said only 
six reporters would be allowed in the room during the proceedings 
and they would have to share their information 
robert hemley a lawyer representing media organizations 
including the associated press had told the judge there would be 
publicity regardless of whether the questioning of jurors was 
public 
the issue then is what is happening in the voir dire 
process that is different or more damaging than previous pretrial 
publicity hemley said 
zaccaros lawyers charles tetzlaff and thomas sherrer had 
requested the order and addison county states attorney john quinn 
did not object quinn said he also was concerned about the jury 
pool noting that the case has received widespread publicity 
because of ferraros prominence 
zaccaro is charged with sale of a regulated drug for allegedly 
selling cocaine to undercover agent laura manning after she came to 
his offcampus apartment and said she heard he could sell her drugs 
zaccaro also had been charged with possession of cocaine with 
intent to sell based on evidence police had found in zaccaros 
car including eight grams of cocaine and documents described as 
records of drug transactions 
but the charge was dismissed because of problems with the search 
warrant and the lack of other evidence to prove the charge 
the case has wound its way slowly through the vermont courts 
zaccaros attorneys challenged several aspects of the case and 
claimed unsuccessfully that zaccaro was singled out for prosecution 
because of his famous mother who ran on the democratic ticket in 
1984 with walter mondale 
tetzlaff and sherrer were unsuccessful in having the case thrown 
out altogether the vermont supreme court refused to dismiss the 
charges 
