<TEXT>
ko sukje lined up 50 pairs of roller 
skates in neat rows as a spring breeze whipped across the square 
and hundreds of people whirled around on bikes and skates 
spring is the best season everyone comes out ko said with 
a smile as he tugged on his red baseball cap 
another bitterly cold korean winter has come and gone a pale 
spring sun drew out crowds from thousands of small apartments where 
they had been cooped up for five months 
purple and yellow blooms were just starting to unfold on trees 
and bushes on the edges of yoido square 
the milelong tarmac square is one of the few open spaces in the 
bustling city of 10 million and people flock to it once warm 
weather arrives 
the city main site of the 1988 summer olympics has few public 
parks or other open areas and many people live in drab concrete 
apartment buildings that stretch for miles around the city 
theres no space in seoul said ko the skate renter this 
is the only place in the city where theres space 
on this balmy day students children and whole families had 
come to yoido to rent bikes or roller skates and just ride round 
and round 
we feel free said kim miji a college student who was 
skipping afternoon classes to go bike riding with her friends we 
enjoy ourselves a lot 
thousands of bikes and skates were lined up on one side of the 
square waiting to be rented for about a dollar rows of shoes were 
piled by the skates as their owners whirled across the square or 
struggled to keep their balance 
children whooped and laughed as they darted around on red bikes 
decorated with picutres of rambo brandishing a grenade launcher 
theres nowhere to ride bikes at home so we cant have them 
said one boy 
everywhere across the city of giant office buildings and clogged 
streets people were enjoying their first breath of spring they 
strolled the sidewalks or stood on street corners watching the 
world go by and chatting with friends 
sidewalk vendors offered chestnuts hot potatos and dried squid 
women with stoves on carts fried onion pancakes and stirred pots 
simmering with noodles in red pepper sauce 
flowers flowers shouted other vendors offering the first 
red blue and yellow blooms from the warmer south pedestrians 
stopped to inspect the bouquets and some brought a bunch to take 
home 
a few vendors sold imported bananas for the equivalent of 125 
each imported fruit is classified as a luxury and heavily taxed 
hundreds of old men stood around in large groups or strolled at 
pagoda park one of the few parks in central seoul some played a 
board game called jangi and bets were changing hands 
most of the retirees were dressed in western suits but a few 
wore traditional korean fur hats snug silk jacks and long loose 
linen pantaloons 
sidewalk fortune tellers did a brisk business as people came to 
ask if the spring would bring luck or if romance was in the offing 
many people come to know their fortunes for the year said 
an old fortune teller sitting on a blanket surrounded by 
astrological charts in chinese and korean 
asked for his name he laughed 
im 70 years old he said waving a visitor away 
