editors note president reagans aids commission appeared to 
be a sinking ship when a retired navy admiral took the helm last 
fall adm james d watkins guided the commission through 
exhaustive hearings that resulted in recommendations that were 
widely praised the admiral is the first to concede however that 
the commission has yet to deal with some of the thorniest questions 
swirling around aids 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
adm james d watkins remembers the advice 
that some of his closest friends offered when he asked them if he 
should take the helm of president reagans embattled aids 
commission 
james its a loser stay out of it 
that was last october the commission was sinking fast in a 
choppy sea of public ridicule and internal disarray the first 
chairman a physician unschooled in the ways of backstage 
washington had resigned critics were portraying the panel as a 
hopeless collection of doctrinaire archconservatives sprinkled 
with a few doctors who nonetheless knew little about aids 
i knew it was a can of worms of the first order watkins 
sats 
but he did not rise to chief of naval operations by doubting his 
own abilities moreover he was a washington veteran 
as a result watkins was more disposed to listen to other 
friends who told him i dont know anybody else who could do it 
i think you ought to try it 
still watkins knew his commission colleagues would not 
automatically salute his elevation to chairman 
i knew i would need their support at the outset so i made 
some calls he recalled in a recent interview id say what 
do you want do you want me to do it or not youve got to let me 
run it if im going to do it 
i got a positive response from all the commissioners i knew 
then i could probably make it there was no divisiveness they knew 
they were in trouble they all had professional reputations at 
stake they saw in me an opportunity 
run it he did 
watkins presented 60 pages of detailed chairmans 
recommendations for the commissions approval on feb 29 
including a call for spending an additional 20 billion over the 
next decade most of it on drug abusers three days later in a pro 
forma business meeting that took all of 10 minutes the panel 
adopted them unanimously 
in releasing the interim report watkins said we waste a lot 
of rhetoric and excessive time on a couple of little issues while 
the forest behind us is burning we believe some major changes in 
course are necessary 
the chorus of editorials lauding those recommendations was as 
loud as the one writing off the commission as a lost cause six 
months and nearly 400 witnesses earlier 
rep henry waxman dcalif a frequent critic of administration 
aids policies praised the watkins report as a firstrate set of 
recommendations that begin to deal with the aids epidemic 
responsibly and in detail 
dr mervyn silverman president of the los angelesbased 
american foundation for aids research said i continue to get 
more and more pleased as i see what watkins is doing 
admittedly the suggestions in the report to the president do 
not get at the thorniest questions swirling around aids 
watkins knows that he ticks off the remaining ones in shorthand 
form education testing confidentiality discrimination legal 
liability pharmaceutical doctors 
were really going to face some toughies he says but 
now were kind of trained weve been through the mill together 
watkins concedes that neither he nor the other members of the 
original panel knew much about aids when they started 
in retrospect it is clear that watkins went about managing the 
aids commission much the way he operated in the navy by immersing 
himself and his associates in a problem until answers floated to 
the surface 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0207 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a favorite watkins phrase is the lights came on 
when he joined the joint chiefs of staff in 1982 as chief of 
naval operations watkins said i knew i had a weakness in the 
area of strategic planning strategic arms limitation talks i 
didnt have a good grasp of that area i knew it was going to be 
one of my primary responsibilities so independent of anything else 
going oni started an education program for myself 
i didnt know what the answer was going to be i had no idea 
but by about january 1983 i had been in it up to my eyeballs with 
my own staff 
the light came on in my own mind my god why dont we play to 
our strength instead of the soviet strength and our strength was 
technology applied technology not theoretical technology 
from that light as watkins tells it the other service 
chiefs lined up with him in recommending to the president that he 
consider moving to a defenseoriented nuclear strategy 
ergo the emergence of reagans strategic defense initiative 
sdi star wars 
im a strategy builder watkins says thats my business 
knowing a lot about how to deal with large groups of individuals to 
try to build programs that are built out of consensus not out of 
directive 
this is the approach i tried to take with the commission 
listen to the witnesses package up what they were saying rather 
than what was coming out of my preconceived notions that might be 
there 
its taken us time to come up on this learning curve 
with so many witnesses telling the commission essentially the 
same thing watkins heard the switches clicking again 
the lights come on here he said in research the lights 
come on in care were uncovering major problems in the health care 
delivery system the lights come on in iv drug abuse and its 
potential to be the longer term specter in aids transmission 
indeed if there is any criticism of the commissions initial 
report on the relatively noncontroversial aids issues dealt with 
so far it might be that the panel has yet to meet a recommendation 
it didnt like most but not all involve spending more money 
watkins notes that the report is quite specific and that it is 
not within the commissions charter to deal with government budget 
priorities 
the admiral and his wife of 37 years have reared six children on 
a navy salary they have seven grandchildren they are not wealthy 
before taking on the job as chairman of the aids commission 
watkins a member of the carnegie council on adolescent 
development was shaping what his resume calls a national program 
for personal excellence in youth to emphasize good education 
good health and good motivation 
relying on foundation grants and charitable contributions that 
work allowed him to supplement his retirement pay modestly he 
says without running afoul of federal bans against retired 
officers jumping immediately into the private and lucrative side of 
the defense business 
other federal rules against double dipping bar watkins from 
being paid for his work on the aids commission its a big 
chore he says its a fulltime job im going to be hurt 
financially by it ive got to be sensitive to that 
when the commission expires this summer watkins says he wants 
to continue his philanthropic work but he also says he needs 
to make some money 
the oneyear ban on his working for private defense companies 
will have long since expired by then watkins is a graduate of the 
nuclear reactor engineering course at the oak ridge national 
laboratory and he says work in commercial nuclear power industry is 
one possibility 
he acknowledges that his work on the aids commission is likely 
to enhance his reputation and enable him to emerge as a much 
betterknown public figure than he was before 
but it might not have worked out that way he said 
</TEXT>
