<TEXT>
with little more than a big mouth and a 
prayer 17yearold estelle williams left her rural alabama home 
more than a halfcentury ago and headed north to pittsburgh with 
the idea that life would be better for an ambitious young woman 
with big plans 
i was never happy in the south i was never happy with life 
for blacks there she said i wanted better things and i saw no 
way of getting them in the south 
mrs williams now 71 was one of nearly a million blacks who 
left the south between 1915 and 1940 in hope of finding a better 
life in the north 
the human aspects of the great migration are examined in a 
traveling exhibit called field to factory afroamerican 
migration 19151940 
a ku klux klan membership card the photograph of a hanging 
tree used in lynchings and tools blacks used while working in the 
industrial north are among the items included in the exhibit it is 
a smaller version of one already in place at the smithsonian 
institutions national museum of american history in washington 
documents letters to relatives photographs and other items 
from that period are on a twoyear national tour that began at 
carnegie mellon university in pittsburgh and ends at the south 
carolina state museum in columbia sc in august 1990 said 
spencer crew a museum familylife curator who spearheaded both 
projects 
other stops are scheduled in jacksonville fla yonkers ny 
baltimore birmingham ala and columbus ohio 
whether youre black or white moving is something a lot of 
people have done crew said many people have relatives who 
left rural areas and moved to northern cities or immigrants who 
moved from other countries to this country 
mrs williams began planning her move when she was in grade 
school she was inspired by an aunt from pittsburgh who frequently 
visited her southern relatives telling them about life in 
pennsylvania 
i was more or less a rebellious young lady she said my 
mother worked in white peoples houses on farms and she tried to 
make we work on the farm but i refused i told her id stay inside 
the house id wash iron cook or anything but i wasnt born to 
work in the fields 
after contributing to her familys support she saved the rest 
of the 50 cents she weekly earned cooking and cleaning in the homes 
of whites eventually she had enough for oneway train fare to 
pittsburgh 
when she arrived she quickly realized her vision of the north as 
a land of limitless opportunity wasnt accurate 
racism existed in pennsylvania also she said and living and 
working conditions in the big city werent much better sometimes 
they were worse 
when i saw where my aunt lived she had one little room and 
the use of a kitchen i nearly died she said 
in her hometown of clayton ala at least we had a big barn 
to stay in but i told myself i made this big brag that i was 
going to pittsburgh so im not going back 
in the following 54 years mrs williams raised two children and 
a niece survived an unhappy marriage bought a home saved enough 
money to bring her mother a brother and two sisters out of alabama 
and helped unionize fellow seamstresses in a wholesale carpeting 
business 
blacks began leaving the south in large numbers for a variety of 
reasons according to joe trotter a carnegie mellon professor of 
history boll weevil infestation and flooding ravaged cotton crops 
at that time limiting the number of farm jobs available for 
blacks while restrictions on immigration during world war i 
increased the number of jobs in industrial northern states 
blacks could not vote in the south and many sought greater 
control over their lives in the north trotter said 
lynching was a real factor for some people it was the whole 
idea that life was precarious in the south he said 
the migration also marked an important turning point in black 
history he said 
previously movement often was into rural areas migration 
into urban industrial areas was something new in fact it 
reorganized the black community and created a national black 
community before it was pretty much a regional southern 
community trotter said 
it took about a year to collect materials for the exhibits some 
personal items were lent to the museum by people who made the 
change from rural to city life crew said 
the larger exhibit in washington includes a farm house from 
southern maryland a recreation of the interior of a segregated 
train car and the inside of a philadelphia row house 
i gave talks for about a year to people telling them what we 
were trying to do crew said it made a lot of people look back 
and see that this was not a singular experience for their relatives 
it was part of a larger story and it fits into a broader 
experience 
it also reminded people of the importance of saving everyday 
artifacts to tell the story of the american people 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

