<TEXT>
introducing youngsters to the marvels of plant life is one of 
the educational benefits of a childrens garden which also 
stimulates a sense of wonder and a respect for living things 
thats the view of the brooklyn botanic garden where for 74 
years more than 15000 children have cultivated the same patch of 
city land in the worlds oldest continuous program of its kind 
the success of the crops is only one of the rewards the 
children reap says betsy jacobs the gardens associate director 
of education childrens programs of equal importance are the 
lessons they learn selfdiscipline firsthand experience 
dignity of labor generosity respect for the rights and property 
of others respect for the environment responsibility and giving 
of ones self 
gardening is an acceptable way for youngsters to get dirt under 
their fingernails and learn something valuable they will hold dear 
for the rest of their lives even the difficult child can respond 
with innocent wonderment to the miracle of growing things 
how do parents or teachers involve youngsters in home gardening 
here are some suggestions from specialists 
start small 5 square feet is a large responsibility for a 
child begin with seeds because if you buy plants your child will 
miss out on the cycle of seeds soil sun and water the best way 
for a child to learn is by watching so keep the coaching to a 
minimum let them watch you for a while before you turn them loose 
to plant 
never water or care for the plants yourself except when 
helping very young children dont lay a guilt trip on the child if 
flowers or vegetables die of neglect say nothing the child 
learned a lesson that may stick 
put a low wire edging around the childs garden which may be 
a separate area in the home garden or a bit of separate land the 
wire is intended to keep out siblings household pets and adult 
feet it also gives the child a sense of ownership let your young 
gardener pull up some flowers if he or she wants to and to make 
bouquets in vases or foillined cans 
a simple device to help children water plants is a roller 
paint tray with holes perforated with a nail plant seeds in rows 
parallel to the tray about 6 inches away the tray can be filled 
with a small bucket and will act as a reservoir a water hose in 
the hands of a little one tends to wash away seeds and knock over 
seedlings and soak the child 
manure water or a weak solution of fertilizer can be used 
occasionally to demonstrate that plants can benefit from extra 
feedings explain what plant foods do for flowers and vegetables 
let the child be a part of the process of selecting what to 
plant but remember that ease and dependability are big factors 
it would be difficult to find an easiertogrow more dependable 
and spectacular plant than annual sunflowers children will get a 
kick out of growing such enormous plants the seeds are easy to 
handle and quick to sprout few insects bother sunflowers beans 
and summer squash seeds also are easy to handle 
climbing vines such as morning glories also make good first 
flowers but you should string these plants up a fence or sturdy 
pole easy flower varieties include marigolds zinnias and cosmos 
another idea is to buy mixtures of flower seeds readymade for 
children some are sold as annual flower mixture cutflower 
mixture or wildflower mixture any of these can produce 
beautiful species and curiosities these mixtures thrive even if 
not thinned much fed or watered for a while 
the idea is to get the childs attention and hold interest with 
projects that get quick or spectacular results 
first show children the dry or sleeping seeds and how they 
wake up when moistened or planted line the inside of a clear 
glass or jar with seeds a few inches apart put a lid on leave the 
jar on a kitchen counter making sure the towel remains wet in a 
few days seeds will swell and burst open roots will grow down 
while stems and leaves grow up 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

