<TEXT>
the brooklyn botanic garden whose childrens garden was 
initiated in 1914 says it has never produced a satisfactory answer 
to the radish question explaining 
every year there has been a saturday in late april when 
packets of seeds are given to several hundred city children the 
soil is carefully worked and the seeds dropped into rows according 
to arrangements meticulously worked out on graph paper during 
classroom sessions weeks before 
the first harvest comes in about six weeks the first harvest 
inevitably is radishes the child never having produced a miracle 
before bears them home in triumph 
then comes for a mother the supreme test of her nurturing 
ability how do you respond to this peculiar prize without 
diminishing the young gardeners enthusiasm and selfesteem 
the lettuce and tomatoes are still weeks and months away 
respectively so you cant make a salad to fry a radish is out of 
the question a little bit may punch up a casserole but theres no 
way it can be a main ingredient the child wants everyone to make a 
meal of the first crop which is indeed a miracle given the 
circumstances 
whats a mother to do 
it is estimated that each child on a certain saturday in 
june takes home an average of 73 radishes as this has been 
happening since 1914 it means that the heroic mothers or brooklyn 
and other new york city boroughs have had as many as 2 million 
radishes to deal with 
