<TEXT>
sooner or later pet economic theories become 
battered by events and must be recycled through academe before 
reappearing in altered form 
it is for this reason that several of the old economic models 
monetary keynesian and supply side among them are in for a 
periodic overhaul while a new one based mainly on recent 
experience is attracting attention 
perhaps most interesting at least from a popular view is that 
it offers an optimistic view of things at a time when some of the 
old models are flashing warnings lights and setting off sirens and 
bells 
edward yardeni of prudentialbache securities calls his version 
new wave economics basing it not on any lab theory of what the 
economy should be doing but simply on what it has been doing 
among its conclusions is this gem economywide recessions are 
unlikely to occur in the future more likely there will be rolling 
recessions limited to certain industries and sections of the 
country 
the viewpoint has a solid basis in recent and current economic 
matters it describes for example the very thing that has been 
occurring in the us economy over the past five years although 
disguised by traditional measures 
the traditional view is that the us economy has expanded 
steadily for five long years and that therefore it is becoming 
old weary and destined to fall into recession 
wait a minute say less traditional economists national figures 
do indeed show an uninterrupted expansion but national figures 
tend to hide what has happened in specific industries and regions 
within the nation 
the most obvious example of national figures disguising rather 
than revealing is how the boom in the northeast and in certain 
other areas badly warped the national numbers for nearly two years 
between 1985 and 1987 
while the massachusetts service economy couldnt be stopped in 
that time the industries and economies of 31 other states mainly 
those involved with or related to agriculture oil and other 
natural resources couldnt get started 
sindlinger amp co economic and marketing analysts repeatedly 
pointed this out consumer confidence payrolls spending and other 
measurements also suggested it 
the truth was always there in the official statistics most 
analysts however chose the national averages instead for one 
thing federal economic policy swings more on national rather than 
regional numbers 
but in yardenis opinion the bond market including a global 
market for us treasury securities is likely to be a more 
effective economic guide than federal reserve policy protecting 
the economy from booms that lead to busts 
it will react faster to dampen booms which suggests that the 
severe busts will no longer be necessary to unwind the excess 
caused by the booms excesses wont be allowed to build up in the 
first place 
if he and likethinkers are correct there may be regional 
recessions in the future as there was for almost two years between 
memorial day 1985 and and february 1987 but national recessions 
will be rarer 
in fact it might be argued that rather than facing a recession 
in the next year or so the us economy might already have put one 
behind it a regional recession that just didnt count in the 
national statistics 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

