<TEXT>
for housewives like kazuko higo beef is a delicacy 
she can afford only rarely almost as infrequently as her three 
grown sons come to visit she laments 
japanese beef is so expensive she said while doing her 
shopping at tokyos peacock supermarket i only cook it on 
occasions when my sons come to visit once every two weeks 
for shoppers at peacock japanese sirloin costs 450 yen per 100 
grams or 1636 a pound 
a similar australian cut sells for 1382 a pound american 
sirloin when it can be found retails at a relatively inexpensive 
745 a pound 
the staggering difference in price between the domestic and 
imported meat is behind the american demand that japan drop all 
import restrictions on beef citrus fruits and other agricultural 
products 
increased sales of us beef in japan could shrink the record 
598 billion us trade deficit with japan 
through a stringent quota system japan limits beef imports to 
protect its politically powerful farmers who support the ruling 
liberal democratic party they are currenty guaranteed 70 percent 
of the beef used locally the remaining 30 percent is imported 
highlevel talks between the two nations on terminating the 
import quotas ended in failure late thursday in washington as japan 
refused us demands japan has maintained it will only increase 
its quotas not drop them entirely 
japan nearly doubled its annual quota for highgrade american 
beef imports since 1983 under a fouryear agreement that expired 
thursday its overall quota for beef imports was raised by a 
smaller amount 
the united states said it would petition the general agreement 
on tariffs and trade an international forum that oversees trade 
rules to have the import quota procedures deemed illegal 
prime minister noboru takeshita said monday he would decide 
japans negotiating position by may 4 the date a gatt panel takes 
up the us grievance 
mrs higo said my sons prefer american beef theyre only 
concerned about volume in their meat and are not too particular 
about the taste 
but my husband and i we prefer japanese beef its so much 
more tender and better tasting also its a lot easier on the 
teeth added the 48yearold housewife 
tsukasa yanagi assistant manager at peacock said the store 
sells about 154 pounds of japanese beef a day but regulations 
limit it to selling only 28 pounds of american beef a day 
of course if our store quota is increased we can sell a lot 
more said yanagi by the end of the day the foreign beef is 
always sold out because its much cheaper 
wed like to be able to keep more american beef he added 
our no 1 priority is to provide customers with tasty but 
inexpensive meat 
yanagi said the stores beef prices and sales quotas are set by 
the quasigovernmental livestock industry promotion corporation 
lipc 
that organization set up in 1961 to regulate and stabilize beef 
prices handles about 80 percent of the meat sold nationwide said 
mitsuru yoshida a director at the organization 
he said the ministry of agriculture forestry and fisheries 
annually decides the floor and ceiling wholesale prices for 
domestic beef 
the price of the imported beef is then fixed according to its 
nearest corresponding japanese cut 
when the wholesale prices are decided the beef both imported 
and domestic is channeled to distributors and normal costs 
including retailers profits are added 
once the meat is on the supermarket shelves if the price of 
the domestic beef shoots up the amount of the imported beef is 
increased yoshida said if the price of the japanese beef 
falls the foreign meat is pulled back from the market 
but if the price of japanese beef fails to rise the lipc will 
buy the meat and keep it in stock yoshida said 
this nontariff barrier is typical of japanese efforts to 
cushion local industries against foreign competition 
zenchu the central union of agricultural cooperatives is also 
going after the heart and mind of the japanese consumer it has 
produced a video showing what it claims are the harmful side 
effects of eating imported food loaded with preservatives and 
chemicals said a spokeswoman for the alljapan agricultural cinema 
association which produced the 30minute movie 
titled even then would you still eat it the video alleges 
that monkeys fed imported food gave birth to deformed babies while 
the number of japanese children falling sick after eating the food 
has increased 
the spokeswoman said about 2000 copies of the video have been 
sold at 80 a copy since it was released in january most to 
agricultural concerns 
