<TEXT>
for the decades when fw woolworth cos 
fiveanddimes dotted the retail landscape the company symbolized 
homespun american merchandising 
but changing times and consumer taste forced the 109yearold 
company to take harsh measures to keep that image from fading like 
an old tintype photograph 
those efforts paid off so well in terms of the bottom line that 
woolworth not only returned to the path of profitability but now 
lies in the takeover path of marylands raiding haft family 
the hafts who have left a string of aborted acquisition 
attempts for other major retailers in their wake said in 
government documents that they intend to buy up to 15 million in 
woolworth stock in what could be the first step in a takeover bid 
for all their overtures the fatherandson team of herbert and 
robert haft and their dart group corp is short on the retail 
tradition woolworth is steeped in 
founded in 1879 by upstate new york farmboy frank woolworth the 
chain pioneered the fivecent counter which carried everything 
from bobby pins to real crystal glasses woolworths 
rummagesale prices allowed the homemaker of yesteryear to outfit a 
kitchen with gadgetry from potato mashers to frying pans for just a 
few dollars 
the publics welcoming of woolworth with open pocketbook spurred 
the company to add a 10cent line in turn forcing a name change to 
woolworths 5 and 10 cent store 
while the fiveanddime label still sticks the description 
became a misnomer in 1932 when the company could no longer sell its 
products for 5 and 10 cents woolworth spokesman jf carroll said 
the 60story headquarters in lower manhattan the company built 
in 1913 replete with gargoyles and patterned after a gothic 
cathedral was a testament to the chains status among its peers 
but woolworths rankings slipped consistently in recent years 
in 1979 it was the nations fourth largest today it is no 13 
ss kresge co always lurking nearby as a major competitor 
surpassed woolworths long ago by successful suburban expansion 
through k mart the name kresge adopted in 1977 
woolworth began to lose its footing when it rode a 
diversification wave in the early 1960s by starting woolco discount 
department stores 
woolco which became too big too fast and whose growth took 
place without direction would become the companys major 
weakness the late chairman edward f gibbons once said 
the division rang up 21 billion of the corporations 72 
billion in sales in 1981 but woolco had to keep borrowing to 
support its sales growth and ultimately failed to make any money 
by 1983 woolworth had closed all 336 woolco stores in the united 
states it sold its majority interest in its british subsidiary and 
took a 435 million aftertax writeoff 
they bit the bullet and ever since they have done a superb job 
of turning things around said stewart spector a vice president 
at furman selz mager dietz amp birney getting rid of woolco is 
what did it he noted 
the comeback was remarkable analysts agree woolworth quickly 
began spending hundreds of millions of dollars to upgrade its 
stores and product line even though it still remains a 
merchandiser of lowerpriced goods 
during woolco the us variety stores were starved for 
attention in capital woolworths carroll said to date more than 
400 stores have been refurbished 
today woolworth has 1695 general merchandise stores and 4614 
specialty stores which include kinney shoes foot locker and lady 
foot locker athletic shops kids mart afterthoughts and richman 
brothers co 
for the fiscal year ended jan 30 woolworth reported profits of 
251 million on sales of 71 billion in the previous year the 
company reported net income of 214 million on sales of 65 
billion 
the company opened the first of a new downsized unit called 
woolworth express in flint mich last fall the conveniencetype 
store is a prototype for 15 others expected to be completed this 
year 
similarly the hafts dart group established as a 
washingtonarea discount drug chain in the 1950s made its mark as 
a discounter but industry analysts see the company these days more 
as a predator than a retailing competitor 
after several takeover attempts the hafts have yet to purchase 
a single store although they have made hundreds of millions of 
dollars from payments and profits on their stock holdings in 
companies they have attempted to take over 
those include dayton hudson corp supermarkets general corp 
safeway stores inc and most recently stop amp shop cos 
one analyst noted that the hafts have made more money as losers 
than many raiders make as winners 
</TEXT>
