<TEXT>
a federal appeals court monday upheld jc 
penney cos defense of a company policy which permits medical and 
dental insurance coverage of a penney employees spouse only if the 
spouse earns less than the employee 
a threejudge panel of the 6th us circuit court of appeals 
ruled 21 that the head of household provision of penneys 
insurance plan is lawful under title vii of the federal civil 
rights act of 1964 
the appeals courts majority ruled that the requirement is legal 
because it is not sexbased but is instead conditioned on a head 
of household status 
the court ruled against the equal employment opportunity 
commission which argued that the policy amounts to unequal 
treatment of penneys female employees and was therefore illegal 
discrimination based on an employees sex 
us district judge robert demascio in detroit ruled at trial 
that the policy did have an unequal impact on female employees but 
he said the eeoc had not proven that jc penney co had a 
discriminatory motive in adopting the requirement 
the appeals courts majority ruled that demascio correctly 
dismissed the eeocs complaint because penneys policy does not 
violate federal civil rights law 
the appellate majority found that penney adopted the head of 
household requirement in order to provide spouse insurance only for 
employees who most needed the coverage those without more highly 
paid spouses the requirement also is an efficient administrative 
tool for avoiding providing coverage of spouses most likely to have 
coverage from their own employers the appeals courts majority 
said 
this is a legitimate business justification for choosing this 
method of supplying an insurance coverage benefit the majority 
ruled in an opinion written by appeals judge danny boggs 
in a minority dissent judge douglas hillman said he would have 
reversed demascios ruling hillman said he did not find penneys 
defense of its insurance coverage policy legitimate 
title viis prohibition against compensation practices that 
discriminate against women employees does not vary with the type of 
compensation chosen by the employer hillman wrote 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

