<TEXT>
a holding company controlled by the belzberg 
family of canada has agreed to pay a 400000 fine to settle a 
lawsuit charging its 1986 purchase of ashland oil co stock 
violated an antitakeover law 
the settlement between the federal trade commission and first 
city financial corp ltd of vancouver british columbia was made 
public in court papers filed last week in us district court here 
the ftc charged in a lawsuit filed friday along with the 
proposed settlement that first city violated the hartscottrodino 
antitrust law by failing to notify the government of ashland stock 
purchases exceeding 15 million 
the complaint charged that first city and its parent roxboro 
investments ltd had also violated the law by continuing to 
purchase more than a 15 million stake in ashland without notifying 
the ftc and observing a 30day waiting period 
first city said in a statement it did not violate the 
hartscottrodino act but agreed to settle to avoid the expense 
of singlehandedly litigating a longstanding interpretive dispute 
between the ftc and the investment community 
the settlement must be given final approval by us district 
judge john h pratt 
the oil companys stock rose 10 percent following a march 25 
1986 announcement that the belzbergs had acquired 92 percent of 
ashland stock and offered to pay 60 a share to buy a controlling 
interest in the kentuckybased refining company 
on april 2 1986 the belzberg companies sold their 92 percent 
stake in ashland for 1341 million under an agreement with the oil 
company 
first city is also a defendant in a parallel action brought in 
federal court here by the securities and exchange commission 
arising from the transaction 
the sec suit charges that first city arranged for its brokerage 
house bear stearns amp co to buy and hold shares of ashland stock 
so that the canadian firm could avoid the premerger notifcation 
requirements 
first city has denied there was any understanding with bear 
stearns 
</TEXT>
