<TEXT>
irving bank corp predicted monday that it would 
earn a profit of more than 200 million in 1988 and it urged 
shareholders again to reject as inadequate bank of new yorks 
hostile 108 billion tender bid 
meanwhile the banking concern said it filed a lawsuit in state 
court attempting to block a proxy solicitation of bank of new york 
which began its tender offer last month and is seeking to gain 
control of irvings board of directors 
in a letter to shareholders sent over the weekend irving 
forecast 1988 net income of 234 million or about 1178 a share 
on revenue of 114 billion 
last year irving reported a loss of 1933 million compared 
with a net profit of 1281 million or 683 in 1986 largely due 
to its increased loanloss provision to cover shaky third world 
debt 
irving attributed the projected improvement in part to 
continued strong performance in its domestic and community banking 
businesses 
your company is performing in line with the 1988 forecast 
based on the results of the first two months of 1988 the letter 
said book value per share is projected to increase to 
approximately 50 from 4091 at dec 31 1987 
bank of new yorks offer represents a multiple of only 12 
times irvings forecasted book value it said 
bank of new york spokesman owen brady said we dont know the 
basis on which the calculated projections were made we cant make 
a meaningful comment 
bank of new yorks current offer of 15 in cash and 1575 
shares of its own stock for each of irvings roughly 181 common 
shares outstanding has been denounced as inadequate by irvings 
board 
last month bank of new york began its tender offer after 
receiving the goahead from the securities and exchange commission 
and the company assembled a slate of 16 nominees to irvings board 
bank of new york currently holds a 483 percent stake in irving 
irving has repeatedly stressed its desire to remain independent 
and has taken a number of steps to spurn bank of new yorks 
advances including instituting an antitakeover poison pill 
intended to make any hostile buyout prohibitively expensive 
irvings lawsuit filed in state court seeks damages in excess 
of about 350 million 
it claims that bank of new yorks proxy material is false and 
misleading particularly in the way it valued irvings portfolio of 
third world debt irving claimed the portfolio was overstated by 
about 208 million 
the suit was filed late last week and mentioned in a filing with 
the securities and exchange commission said david santos an 
irving spokesman 
brady called the suit without merit and said the banking 
concern would seek a dismissal 
